IMPLEMENTATION BRIEF FOR HERMES
Project
Biologically Plausible Free-Energy Competitive Neural Architecture


Objective
Implement a biologically grounded spiking neural microcircuit that models:


     • Local synaptic learning only
     • Continuous online learning
     • Stateful leaky integrate-and-fire dynamics
     • Temporal competition between excitatory neurons
     • Shared lateral inhibition
     • Refractory periods
     • Neuronal specialization
     • Predictive feedback
     • Suppression of predicted sensory input
     • Residual neural activity as prediction error
     • Approximate free-energy minimization
     • Automatic reduction and stopping of learning after specialization
     • Recruitment of unused neurons for novel patterns

Do not implement this as a standard artificial neural network, multilayer perceptron, or classifier with a
separate training stage.


The primary goal is biological and dynamical plausibility.


1. High-Level Circuit
Build a minimal cortical microcircuit containing:


     • 3 sensory input neurons
     • 5 excitatory neurons: E1–E5
     • 1 shared inhibitory neuron: I1
     • Pattern-specific predictive feedback pathways

Basic competition architecture:


               Sensory Inputs
                  x1 x2 x3


                   \ | /
           -------------------
           E1 E2 E3 E4 E5
            \ \ | / /
                I1
               |
        inhibition to E-pool


Predictive feedback architecture:


  Specialized E-neuron
          |
          v
  Pattern-specific inhibitory feedback
          |
          v
  Relevant sensory inputs


The shared inhibitory neuron and predictive feedback serve two different functions:


    1. Shared I1 creates competition among excitatory neurons.
    2. Pattern-specific feedback suppresses sensory activity already explained by a learned
       representation.

Do not combine these mechanisms unless the implementation preserves their different targets and
functions.


2. Mandatory Biological Constraints
2.1 Stateful Leaky Integrate-and-Fire Neurons
All excitatory and inhibitory neurons must be implemented as stateful LIF neurons.


Do not implement neurons as:


  output = weighted_sum > threshold


That would reduce the model to a perceptron.


Each neuron must preserve state across simulation timesteps.


Required persistent variables include:


     • membrane_potential
     • refractory_timer
     • spiked
     • last_spike_time
     • neuron-specific decay parameters
     • optional persistent synaptic-current variables

Suggested membrane equation:

                                              dV
                                         τm      = −(V − Vrest ) + Isyn
                                              dt
Discrete approximation:

                                                    Δt
                            V (t + 1) = V (t) +        [−(V (t) − Vrest ) + Isyn (t)]
                                                    τm
When:


                                                 V (t) ≥ Vthreshold

the neuron must:


    1. Emit a binary spike.
    2. Reset its membrane potential.
    3. Enter a refractory period.

Required class structure:


  class LIFNeuron:
      def step(self, synaptic_current):
          ...


The neuron state must persist between step() calls.


Do not use a stateless forward() pass.


2.2 Binary Event-Driven Spikes
Spikes must be represented as discrete events:


  0 = no spike
  1 = spike


Do not represent neuron outputs as continuous activations such as:


  0.35
  0.71
  0.92


Membrane potential may be continuous, but emitted spikes must be event based.


2.3 Refractory Periods
Every excitatory and inhibitory neuron must have an explicit refractory timer.


Example:


  refractory_steps = 5


Required behavior:


  if refractory_timer > 0:
      refractory_timer -= 1
      neuron_cannot_spike = True


During the refractory period:


     • The neuron cannot emit another spike.
     • Its membrane potential should remain at reset or follow the selected biological approximation.
     • It must not be selected externally as a winner.

The refractory period is part of the competition mechanism.


Example temporal sequence:


  E2 fires
     ↓
  E2 becomes refractory
     ↓
  E4 may continue integrating


     ↓
  I1 accumulates excitation
     ↓
  Competition continues over time


Do not terminate the competition immediately after the first E-neuron spike.


2.4 Separate Excitatory and Inhibitory Time Constants
Excitatory and inhibitory neurons must not share one global decay parameter.


Use separate values such as:


  tau_e = 20.0
  tau_i = 40.0


Required relationship:


                                                    τI > τE

This allows inhibition to persist longer than excitation.


The implementation should ideally separate:


      • Excitatory membrane time constant
      • Inhibitory membrane time constant
      • Excitatory synaptic-current decay
      • Inhibitory synaptic-current decay

This asymmetry helps stabilize the winner and suppress competitors over a biologically meaningful period.


3. Temporal Competition
3.1 No argmax() Winner Selection
Do not select the winning neuron using:


  winner = np.argmax(activation)


The winner must emerge through the simulation dynamics.


Competition must follow:


  Sensory spikes arrive
          ↓
  All E-neurons integrate over time
          ↓
  One E-neuron reaches threshold first
            ↓
  That E-neuron emits a spike
          ↓
  Its spike drives I1
          ↓
  I1 integrates over time
          ↓
  I1 eventually emits an inhibitory spike
          ↓
  Competing E-neurons are suppressed


The winner is defined operationally as the first neuron to spike during a presentation or competition
window.


The code must record the first spike rather than calculate the largest instantaneous activation.


3.2 Competition Continues After the First Spike
The first spike does not immediately terminate the trial.


Other E-neurons may fire before shared inhibition becomes strong enough.


This behavior is expected during early learning.


Example:


  E2 fires first
  E2 becomes refractory
  E4 fires later
  E5 approaches threshold
  I1 reaches threshold
  I1 suppresses remaining competitors


Over repeated presentations, specialization should cause one neuron to:


     • Fire earlier


      • Fire more reliably
      • Recruit inhibition sooner
      • Reduce later competitor spikes

This is emergent temporal winner-take-all behavior.


4. Shared Lateral Inhibition
All five E-neurons connect excitatorily to I1.


Topology:


  E1 ─┐
  E2 ─┤
  E3 ─┼──> I1
  E4 ─┤
  E5 ─┘


Each E spike adds current to I1.


Example:


  E2 spikes → I1 potential increases
  E4 spikes → I1 potential increases again
  E2 spikes later → I1 reaches threshold
  I1 fires


I1 must not fire automatically after the first E spike unless its actual threshold is crossed.


When I1 fires, it sends inhibitory current to the E-pool:


                                                 VEi ← VEi − wIE

or through a decaying inhibitory synaptic-current variable.


The already-fired winner may be protected temporarily because it is refractory, but the implementation
should not rely on an external condition that permanently exempts the winner.


The network dynamics should determine which neurons are affected at each timestep.


Purpose:


      • Suppress late competitors
      • Prevent several neurons from learning the same pattern
      • Encourage sparse representation
      • Produce winner-take-all competition through time


5. Local Hebbian Learning
Do not use:


      • Backpropagation
      • Gradient descent
      • A global classification loss
      • Batch optimization
      • A train/test split
      • Error signals calculated outside the local circuit

A sensory-to-E synapse may update only using locally available information:


      • Presynaptic sensory spike
      • Postsynaptic E-neuron spike
      • Current synaptic weight
      • Local plasticity state

Basic rule:


                                                 Δwij = ηxj si

where:


      • xj = 1 when sensory neuron j spikes
      • si = 1 when excitatory neuron i spikes

Example:


  if sensory_spikes[j] == 1 and excitatory_spikes[i] == 1:
      weights[i, j] += learning_rate


Mandatory rule:


         A neuron that does not fire does not update its weights.


Residual activity may drive an unused neuron toward threshold, but the neuron must actually fire before
synaptic learning occurs.


Correct sequence:


  Residual sensory spikes
          ↓
  Unused E-neuron integrates
          ↓
  Unused E-neuron reaches threshold
             ↓
  Unused E-neuron fires
          ↓
  Its active local synapses strengthen


Do not update all unused neurons simply because residual activity exists.


6. Learning Saturation
A neuron must not learn indefinitely.


Synapses require a maximum capacity:


                                                0 ≤ wij ≤ wmax

Example:


  weights = np.clip(weights, 0.0, w_max)


Use at least one biologically motivated plasticity-reduction mechanism.


Option A: Synaptic saturation

                                         Δwij = ηxj si (1 −        )
                                                               wij
                                                              wmax

As:


                                                 wij → wmax

the update approaches zero.


Option B: Neuron-level plasticity budget
Each neuron has a finite plasticity variable:


  plasticity_remaining


Each successful learning event reduces that budget.


Option C: Specialization criterion
A neuron becomes specialized when:


      • Its preferred-pattern response latency is sufficiently low.
      • Its preferred weights are near saturation.
      • Its response is stable over repeated trials.
      • Its pattern selectivity exceeds a defined threshold.

After specialization:


  learning_enabled = False


or its learning rate becomes extremely small.


Do not require every weight to equal w_max , because a specialized neuron may represent a sparse pattern
in which inactive-input weights should remain weak.


7. Pattern Exclusivity
A specialized neuron must resist being overwritten by a different pattern.


Example:


  E2 specializes to Pattern A
          ↓
  Pattern B arrives
          ↓
  E2 may recognize an overlapping component
          ↓
  E2 must not rewrite its representation as Pattern B


Mechanisms may include:


      • Plasticity saturation
      • Reduced learning rate
      • Frozen learning after specialization


      • A local novelty or residual condition
      • Strong selectivity requirements

Unused neurons should remain plastic so they can learn unexplained patterns.


Expected result:


  E2 → Pattern A
  E4 → Pattern B
  E1 → Pattern C


rather than:


  E2 repeatedly overwrites its weights for every pattern


8. Predictive Feedback
8.1 Feedforward Representation
When an E-neuron recognizes a pattern and fires, it sends a feedforward spike representing that learned
feature to the next layer.


Example:


  Sensory pattern: [1, 1, 1]
          ↓
  E3 fires
          ↓
  Feedforward meaning: “Pattern represented by E3 is present”


This feedforward spike is a representation, not necessarily prediction error.


8.2 Backward Prediction
A specialized E-neuron must also generate a prediction of the sensory inputs associated with its learned
pattern.


If E3 learned:


  [1, 1, 1]


its feedback prediction should target those sensory inputs.


If E3 learned:


  [1, 0, 1]


its feedback should target inputs 1 and 3, not input 2.


Prediction must therefore be pattern-specific.


The feedback mask can be derived from:


      • Learned sensory weights
      • A stored specialization template
      • Local feedback weights strengthened during learning


8.3 Predictive Cancellation Must Be Implemented as Inhibition
Do not implement prediction only as an offline mathematical subtraction used for plotting.


The circuit must contain an active inhibitory feedback mechanism.


Conceptual flow:


  Specialized E-neuron fires
          ↓
  Activates feedback inhibitory synapses
          ↓
  Relevant sensory neurons receive inhibitory current
          ↓
  Their membrane potential or spike probability decreases


The feedback may be modeled as:


      • Negative synaptic current
      • Reduction in sensory membrane potential
      • Increased sensory firing threshold
      • Temporary inhibitory conductance

The implementation should preserve temporal delay and duration.


Avoid instantly replacing:


  input = input - prediction


unless this is explicitly marked as a temporary simplified approximation.


The preferred implementation is event-driven inhibitory feedback.


9. Distinguish the Two Inhibitory Mechanisms
9.1 Shared lateral inhibition
Path:


  E-pool → I1 → E-pool


Purpose:


        • Competition
        • Winner-take-all behavior
        • Suppression of competing representations

Target:


        • Excitatory pool


9.2 Predictive feedback inhibition
Path:


  Specialized E-neuron → feedback inhibition → sensory layer


Purpose:


        • Cancel predicted sensory activity
        • Reveal unexplained residual activity
        • Reduce redundant sensory processing

Target:


        • Specific sensory inputs associated with the learned pattern


These pathways must be recorded and analyzed separately.


A global shared inhibitory neuron must not suppress the full sensory field indiscriminately, because that
would erase novel sensory components before unused neurons could learn them.


10. Free-Energy Approximation
Do not claim to implement the full mathematical Free Energy Principle involving:


     • Variational Bayesian inference
     • KL divergence
     • Explicit probability distributions
     • A complete probabilistic generative model

Instead, implement a biologically inspired approximation based on predictive cancellation.


Define:


                                         rj (t) = max(0, xj (t) − x
                                                                  ^j (t))

where:


     • xj (t) is sensory activity
      ^j (t) is predicted inhibitory activity
     •x
     • rj (t) is residual unexplained sensory activity

Define the free-energy proxy as:


                                                FE(t) = ∑ rj (t)
                                                              j

Interpretation:


     • High residual activity = high prediction error
     • Low residual activity = low prediction error
     • Zero residual activity = current learned representations explain the sensory input

A preferred description is:


         Residual sensory spikes act as a local neural proxy for prediction error and simplified free
         energy.


11. Separate Free Energy From Total Energy
Do not use total network spike count as the only free-energy measure.


The system may still require:


     • A winner spike
     • An inhibitory spike
     • A feedforward representation spike

even when sensory prediction is accurate.


Track two separate metrics.


11.1 Residual prediction-error metric
                                    F Eresidual = Nunexplained sensory spikes

This is the primary free-energy proxy.


11.2 Total biological activity cost
                       Etotal = Nsensory spikes + NE spikes + NI spikes + Nfeedback events

This approximates the network’s overall energetic cost.


A familiar pattern may produce:


  Winner spikes:           1
  I-neuron spikes:         1
  Residual sensory spikes: 0


This represents low prediction error even though the entire network is not silent.


Do not treat every zero-spike timestep as proof of successful prediction.


12. Residual-Driven Learning
After predictive feedback suppresses the known portion of the input, any unexplained sensory spikes
remain active.


Example:


Learned vertical component:


  0 1 0
  0 1 0
  0 1 0


New plus-sign input:


  0 1 0
  1 1 1
  0 1 0


After vertical prediction:


  0 0 0
  1 0 1
  0 0 0


The remaining horizontal spikes are the residual.


Required process:


  Known component is predicted
          ↓
  Known component is inhibited
          ↓
  Unexplained component remains active
          ↓
  Unused E-neurons integrate residual spikes
          ↓
  One unused neuron reaches threshold
          ↓
  That neuron fires
          ↓
  Its active local synapses strengthen
          ↓
  A new specialization emerges


This is the anomaly-detection and continual-learning mechanism.


13. Dynamic Equilibrium
The goal is not permanent silence.


The desired endpoint is a dynamic equilibrium in which:


      • Familiar patterns are recognized quickly.
      • One sparse representation neuron fires.
      • Predicted sensory activity is suppressed.
      • Residual prediction error is low.
      • Competitors are inhibited.
      • Weights no longer grow unnecessarily.
      • Novel input still produces residual activity.
      • Unused neurons remain available for learning.

A learned pattern should produce lower residual sensory activity than an unlearned pattern.


14. Input Representation
Begin with simple binary patterns using three sensory inputs.


Example patterns:


  pattern_a = [1, 1, 1]
  pattern_b = [1, 0, 1]
  pattern_c = [0, 1, 1]


These names should remain generic unless they truly correspond to spatial vertical, horizontal, or diagonal
patterns.


For real line orientations, use a 3×3 sensory field:


  Vertical:
  0 1 0
  0 1 0
  0 1 0

  Horizontal:
  0 0 0
  1 1 1
  0 0 0


  Diagonal:
  1 0 0
  0 1 0
  0 0 1


Input may be generated using:


     • Repeated deterministic timestep spikes
     • Bernoulli spike trains
     • Poisson spike trains

Start with deterministic spikes for debugging, then add stochastic timing.


15. Required Simulation Order Per Timestep
Use a clearly defined causal update order.


Recommended order:


  1. Generate external sensory spikes.

  2. Apply predictive inhibitory feedback from earlier timesteps.

  3. Update sensory neuron states.

  4. Compute residual sensory spikes.

  5. Deliver residual sensory spikes to E-neurons.

  6. Update E-neuron membrane potentials.

  7. Detect E-neuron spikes.

  8. Record the first E spike as the temporary winner.

  9. Apply local Hebbian updates only for E-neurons that fired.

  10. Deliver E spikes to I1.

  11. Update I1 membrane potential.

  12. Detect an I1 spike.

  13. Deliver delayed inhibitory current from I1 to the E-pool.


  14. Generate pattern-specific feedback events from specialized E-neurons.

  15. Update refractory timers.


  16. Record all states and metrics.


Synaptic effects should ideally have at least a one-timestep delay so causality is explicit.


Avoid allowing a spike to travel through every layer and return within the same timestep unless this is
intentionally documented.


