Experiment 4: Free-energy reduction
Present the same pattern before and after learning.


Track separately:


     • Raw sensory spike count
     • Predicted sensory inhibition
     • Residual sensory spike count
     • E-neuron spikes
     • I-neuron spikes
     • Total network spikes

Expected result:


                                      F Eresidual, after < F Eresidual, before

Do not claim successful free-energy reduction based only on isolated zero-spike timesteps.


Use trial averages or moving averages.


Experiment 5: New-pattern recruitment
After Pattern A has been learned, present Pattern B.


Verify:


      • The specialized Pattern A neuron does not overwrite its representation.
      • Pattern A overlap may still be recognized and cancelled.
      • Residual Pattern B activity remains.
      • An unused E-neuron is recruited.
      • The unused neuron fires before learning.
      • The new neuron specializes to Pattern B.


Experiment 6: Anomaly input
Present:


  Known Pattern A + novel component


Verify:


      • The known component is predicted and suppressed.
      • Novel sensory activity remains.
      • Residual free energy increases relative to the fully familiar pattern.
      • The network can recruit a new representation.


