18. Validation Requirements
The implementation is not considered successful unless all of the following are demonstrated.


Neuron dynamics
     • Membrane state persists across timesteps.
     • Leak is visible.
     • Threshold crossing creates a spike.
     • Reset occurs.
     • Refractory periods prevent immediate refiring.


Competition
     • No argmax() or external winner selection.
     • E-neurons compete through spike timing.
     • I1 integrates E-neuron spikes.
     • I1 inhibition reduces competitor firing.


Learning
     • Only firing neurons update weights.
     • Only active presynaptic synapses strengthen.
     • Weights remain bounded.
     • Plasticity decreases or stops after specialization.
     • Specialized neurons resist overwriting.


Prediction
     • Specialized E-neurons generate pattern-specific feedback.
     • Feedback inhibits only predicted sensory components.
     • Novel components remain active.


Free energy
     • Residual sensory activity is recorded separately.
     • Familiar patterns produce lower residual activity than novel patterns.
     • Total spike cost and residual prediction error are not conflated.
     • A zero-spike timestep is not treated by itself as proof of successful prediction.


