23. Full Intended Process

  1. A sensory pattern produces spikes.

  2. All five excitatory LIF neurons integrate the spikes over time.

  3. One E-neuron reaches threshold first and fires.

  4. The first firing neuron becomes the temporary winner.

  5. The winner enters its refractory period.

  6. Its spike travels to the shared inhibitory LIF neuron.

  7. I1 integrates excitation rather than firing instantly.


8. Other E-neurons may continue competing during the delay.

9. Once I1 reaches threshold, it emits an inhibitory spike.

10. Longer-lasting inhibition suppresses competing E-neurons.


11. Only E-neurons that actually fired update active sensory synapses.

12. Repeated exposure causes one E-neuron to respond earlier and more reliably.


13. The neuron’s preferred synapses approach saturation.

14. Its plasticity gradually decreases or stops.

15. The specialized neuron sends a sparse representation forward.

16. It also generates pattern-specific inhibitory feedback.

17. Predicted sensory activity is reduced.

18. Unexplained sensory spikes remain as residual prediction error.

19. Unused E-neurons integrate the residual activity.

20. If an unused E-neuron fires, it begins learning the unexplained component.

21. Familiar patterns produce progressively less residual activity.

22. Novel patterns continue producing residual spikes.

23. The network reaches a dynamic equilibrium in which known information is
represented sparsely, unnecessary sensory activity is suppressed, and unused
capacity remains available for new learning.\

