12. Required Scientific Validation Tests

Test A: LIF statefulness

Give an E-neuron weak repeated input.

Verify:

Membrane potential rises
No input causes leakage
Closely timed spikes accumulate
Threshold crossing causes a spike
Voltage resets
Refractory period prevents immediate refiring

Failure condition:

The neuron responds only through an instantaneous weighted sum.

Test B: Temporal winner-take-all

Verify:

Sensory input occurs
An E-neuron reaches threshold first
That neuron spikes
I1 begins integrating
I1 spikes later
Competing E-neuron voltages decrease

Record exact timestamps.

Failure conditions:

- Winner selected with argmax()
- I1 fires without integrating
- Inhibition happens in the same instant as the first sensory spike

Test C: Repeated-pattern specialization

Present the same pattern over many trials.

Expected:

- One E-neuron wins increasingly often.
- Its first-spike latency decreases.
- Matching sensory weights strengthen.
- Nonmatching sensory weights remain weak.
- Competitor spikes decrease.
- Plasticity eventually decreases or stops.

Show:

Winner identity by trial
First-spike latency by trial
Weight heatmaps
Number of competing spikes

Test D: Predictive cancellation

After specialization, present the learned pattern.

Verify:

Raw sensory input remains present
Specialized E-neuron fires
Pattern-specific feedback activates
Correct sensory locations are inhibited
Residual activity decreases

The feedback mask must resemble the neuron’s learned receptive field.

Test E: Novel or composite input

After learning a diagonal, present an X-shape.

Expected:

Known diagonal component is inhibited
Unexplained opposite diagonal remains active
Residual free energy is greater than for the familiar diagonal
An unused neuron begins responding to the residual

This is the main test of anomaly detection and continual learning.

13. Required Control Experiments

Disable predictive feedback

Expected:

- Recognition may still occur.
- Residual sensory activity should remain high.
- The familiar-pattern energy reduction should disappear.

Disable shared inhibition

Expected:

- More E-neurons fire.
- Multiple E-neurons may learn the same pattern.
- Winner-take-all specialization becomes weaker.

Shuffle feedback connections

Expected:

- The prediction targets incorrect sensory locations.
- Residual mismatch remains high.
- Cancellation quality becomes worse.

Disable refractory periods

Expected:

- Frequent winners may repeatedly spike.
- Temporal competition changes.
- One neuron may dominate excessively.

Set inhibitory delay to zero

Expected:

- Competition becomes unrealistically instantaneous.
- Other neurons may never get a chance to integrate.

These controls demonstrate that the observed behavior is caused by the intended biological mechanisms.

14. Acceptance Criteria

The implementation is considered successful only when the following are shown.

Familiar pattern

- One neuron becomes selective.
- It fires earlier after learning.
- Its learned weight heatmap matches the pattern.
- It generates matching predictive feedback.
- Residual sensory activity decreases.

Novel pattern

- Familiar components are suppressed.
- Novel components remain active.
- Residual activity is greater than for the familiar pattern.
- An unused neuron can learn the residual.

Competition

- Winner emerges through spike timing.
- I1 fires after E-neuron input.
- Lateral inhibition reduces competitor spikes.
- No external winner-selection function is used.

Energy

- Residual prediction error and total activity are reported separately.
- Energy reduction is averaged over trials or windows.
- Individual zero-spike timesteps are not treated as proof of success.

Biological state

- Membrane potentials persist.
- Leakage occurs.
- Resets occur.
- Refractory timers work.
- Synaptic delays are visible.
- Inhibitory effects persist longer than excitatory effects.

15. Do Not Overclaim the Result

Use this description:

This system is a cortical-column-inspired spiking microcircuit that approximates predictive coding and free-energy minimization through pattern-specific inhibitory cancellation.

Do not state:

This is an exact implementation of Karl Friston’s Free Energy Principle.

Do not state:

The network became silent, therefore prediction is proven correct.

The correct evidence is:

Input was present
        ↓
A learned representation fired
        ↓
Correct feedback was generated
        ↓
Predicted input was selectively suppressed
        ↓
Unexplained residual activity decreased

16. Recommended Development Order

Phase 1: Instrument the backend

Before adding 3D, return:

- Raw sensory spikes
- Prediction
- Residual spikes
- Refractory states
- Winner latency
- Feedback weights
- Residual free energy
- Total activity

Confirm these values numerically.

Phase 2: Add the 3D renderer

Build the Three.js scene and animate existing backend events.

Do not modify model behavior during this phase.

Phase 3: Add scientific controls

Implement:

- Disable feedback
- Disable inhibition
- Disable refractory period
- Shuffle feedback
- Adjustable delays

Phase 4: Add interactive experiments

Implement:

- Draw-your-own 3×3 pattern
- Save learned state
- Reset learning
- Pattern sequence editor
- Familiar versus novel comparison

Phase 5: Add hierarchical columns later

Only after the single-column circuit is validated, add a second level:

Multiple lower columns
        ↓
Higher-level E-pool
        ↓
Combination-pattern learning

Do not add more layers before the single-column cancellation and competition mechanisms have been verified.

My strongest recommendation is to keep both the 2D diagnostic view and the new 3D view. The 3D version will make the architecture easier to understand and present, but the raw-input, prediction, residual, voltage, latency, and energy plots are what will tell you whether the model is truly correct.


